de>.hide()</code>  which do not use the effects queue.</p>\n    <p>Durations are given in milliseconds; higher values indicate slower animations, not faster ones. The strings <code>&apos;fast&apos;</code> and <code>&apos;slow&apos;</code> can be supplied to indicate durations of 200 and 600 milliseconds, respectively.</p>\n    <p>Using the standard effects queue, we can, for example, set an 800-millisecond delay between the <code>.slideUp()</code> and <code>.fadeIn()</code> of <code>&lt;div id=&quot;foo&quot;&gt;</code>:</p>\n    <div class=\"syntaxhighlighter javascript\">\n	<table>\n		<tbody>\n			<tr>\n				\n				<td class=\"gutter\">\n					\n						<div class=\"line n1\">1</div>\n					\n				</td>\n				\n				<td class=\"code\">\n					<pre><div class=\"container\"><div class=\"line\"><code>$( <span class=\"string\">&quot;#foo&quot;</span> ).slideUp( <span class=\"number\">300</span> ).delay( <span class=\"number\">800</span> ).fadeIn( <span class=\"number\">400</span> );</code></div></div></pre>\n				</td>\n			</tr>\n		</tbody>\n	</table>\n</div>\n\n    <p>When this statement is executed, the element slides up for 300 milliseconds and then pauses for 800 milliseconds before fading in for 400 milliseconds.</p>\n    <div class=\"warning\">\n      <p>\n        <strong>The <code>.delay()</code> method is best for delaying between queued jQuery effects. Because it is limited&#x2014;it doesn&apos;t, for example, offer a way to cancel the delay&#x2014;<code>.delay()</code> is not a replacement for JavaScript&apos;s native <a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WindowTimers.setTimeout\">setTimeout</a> function, which may be more appropriate for certain use cases.</strong>\n      </p>\n    </div>\n  ','[\"\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<pre><div class=\\\"container\\\"><div class=\\\"line\\\"><code><span class=\\\"doctype\\\">&lt;!doctype html&gt;</span></code></div></div><div class=\\\"container\\\"><div class=\\\"line\\\"><code><span class=\\\"tag\\\">&lt;<span class